See this [question](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4716503/reading-a-plain-text-file-in-java) for how to read files in Java.
As each line seems to consist of comma separated values, you can just use [split](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#split-java.lang.String-) to get the individual values as array. Using [streams](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/package-summary.html) (or alternatively a for-each loop) you can clean those values, e.g. using [strip](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#strip() ) to remove whitespaces and [replaceAll](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2088037/trim-characters-in-java) to remove the brackets.
For converting the array back into a line, you could use [join](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#join-java.lang.CharSequence-java.lang.CharSequence...-). You can collect the lines using a `String` or better a [StringBuilder](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/StringBuilder.html).

Here is an example:

    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
    try {
        Files.lines(Path.of(&quot;test.txt&quot;)).forEach(x -&gt; {
            String[] split = x.split(&quot;,&quot;);
            split = stream(split).map(y -&gt; {
